  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of legislation to combat money laundering has been a long and complex process, driven by increasing awareness of the threat it poses to financial systems and national security. Here's a breakdown of key milestones and trends:\n\n**Early Stages (Pre-1980s): Focus on Drug Trafficking**\n\n*   **Limited Scope:** Initial efforts were primarily focused on targeting the proceeds of drug trafficking. The focus was not on a broad range of criminal activities.\n*   **Lack of Comprehensive Laws:** Many countries lacked specific laws criminalizing money laundering. Existing laws were often inadequate to address the issue effectively.\n*   **Limited International Cooperation:** Cross-border cooperation on financial crime was minimal.\n\n**Key Milestones & Developments:**\n\n1.  **The US Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970 (US):** This is considered a foundational piece of legislation.\n    *   **Purpose:** To require financial institutions to keep records of cash transactions exceeding a certain threshold and report suspicious activity.\n    *   **Impact:** Laid the groundwork for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations by requiring banks to monitor and report large cash transactions.\n2.  **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** This was one of the first international agreements focused on combatting money laundering.\n\n**The 1980s and 1990s: Expanding the Scope & International Cooperation**\n\n*   **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (US):** This Act criminalized money laundering itself, making it a federal crime to conduct financial transactions with the proceeds of certain unlawful activities.\n*   **Creation of the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) (1989):**\n    *   **Purpose:** An intergovernmental body established",
